206 “ Well,” said Crassus, ‘⁴ since, to keep you with me more easily, I have followed your wishes rather than my own practice or natural bent, what if we ask Antonius to unfold to us all that he is keeping to himself and has not yet published abroad, of which he complained just now that a single little book had already slipped out of his hands, and to disclose those secrets of oratory ? '⁹ “As you please,” replied Sulpicius. “For from the lips of Antonius we shall be learning your own views also.”

207 “ I ask you then, Antonius,’' went on Crassus, “ as this burden is laid upon people of our years by the eagerness of these young men, to express your sentiments upon these matters which you see are required of you.'’
